'generate_query[1].predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ["Aironet Wireless Communications | Cisco Aironet is a maker of wireless networking equipment currently operated as a division of Cisco Systems. It was started by ex-Marconi Wireless employees in 1986 as Telesystems SLW in Canada, right after the United States Federal Communications Commission (FCC) opened up the ISM bands for spread spectrum license-free use. Telxon acquired Telesystems SLW in 1992, and Aironet Wireless Communications was spun off from Telxon's RF Division in 1994. Cisco Systems acquired Aironet in 1999.", "Aironet ARLAN | ARLAN is a family of both proprietary non-802.11 and 802.11-compliant wireless networking technologies developed and marketed by Aironet Wireless Communications in the 1990s prior to Aironet's acquisition by Cisco Systems. Operating in the 900 MHz and 2.4 GHz ISM bands and offering a nominal 2.0 Mbit/s throughput, the non-802.11 DSSS products competed directly with NCR's WaveLAN technology. After acquisition, the ARLAN lineup was renamed to Cisco Aironet; the non-802.11 products were supported briefly then discontinued.", 'AEGIS SecureConnect | AEGIS SecureConnect (or simply ‘AEGIS’) is the former name of a network authentication system used in IEEE 802.1X networks. It was developed by Meetinghouse Data Communications, Inc.; the system was renamed "Cisco Secure Services Client" when Meetinghouse was acquired by Cisco Systems. The AEGIS Protocol is an 802.1X “Supplicant” (i.e. handles authentication for wired and wireless networks, such as those that use WPA-PSK, WPA-Radius, or Certificate-based authentication), and is commonly installed along with a Network Interface Card’s (NIC) or VPN drivers.'], 'question': 'Aironet Wireless Communications, network equipment maker, was acquired in 1999 by which Silicon Valley giant?', 'reasoning': 'Aironet Wireless Communications was acquired by Cisco Systems in 1999.', 'search_query': '"Aironet Wireless Communications acquisition by Cisco Systems"'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Twilight (novel series) | Twilight is a series of four vampire-themed fantasy romance novels by American author Stephenie Meyer. Released annually from 2005 through 2008, the four books chart the later teen years of Isabella "Bella" Swan, a girl who moves to Forks, Washington, and falls in love with a 104-year-old vampire named Edward Cullen. The series is told primarily from Bella\'s point of view, with the epilogue of "Eclipse" and Part II of "Breaking Dawn" being told from the viewpoint of character Jacob Black, a werewolf. The unpublished "Midnight Sun" is a retelling of the first book, "Twilight", from Edward Cullen\'s point of view. The novella "The Short Second Life of Bree Tanner", which tells the story of a newborn vampire who appeared in "Eclipse", was published on June 5, 2010, as a hardcover book and on June 7 as a free online ebook. "" , a definitive encyclopedic reference with nearly 100 full color illustrations, was released in bookstores on April 12, 2011.', 'Twilight (Meyer novel) | Twilight (stylized as twilight) (2005) is a young adult vampire-romance novel by author Stephenie Meyer. It is the first book in the "Twilight" series, and introduces seventeen-year-old Isabella "Bella" Swan, who moves from Phoenix, Arizona to Forks, Washington. She is endangered after falling in love with Edward Cullen, a vampire. Additional novels in the series are "New Moon", "Eclipse", and "Breaking Dawn".', 'Stephenie Meyer | Stephenie Meyer (née Morgan; ; born December 24, 1973) is an American young adult fiction writer and film producer, best known for her vampire romance series "Twilight". The "Twilight" novels have gained worldwide recognition and sold over 100 million copies, with translations into 37 different languages. Meyer was the bestselling author of 2008 and 2009 in America, having sold over 29 million books in 2008, and 26.5 million books in 2009. "Twilight" was the best-selling book of 2008 in US bookstores.'], 'question': 'In which year was the first of the vampire-themed fantasy romance novels for which The Twilight Saga: The Official Illustrated Guide serves as a spin-off encyclopedic reference book first published?', 'reasoning': 'The first book in the "Twilight" series, "Twilight", was published in 2005.', 'search_query': '"Twilight" series first published year'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ["1996 24 Hours of Le Mans | The 1996 24 Hours of Le Mans was the 64th Grand Prix of Endurance, and took place on 15 and 16 June 1996. It was won by a Tom Walkinshaw-Porsche prototype run by Joest Racing with drivers Davy Jones, Manuel Reuter and Le Mans rookie Alexander Wurz completing 354 laps. While not being the fastest car on track, it hit the front in the first hour and aside from several pit-stop overlaps, was never headed as other teams hit mechanical troubles during the race. This was Reuter's second Le Mans victory, and the first for Jones (after finishing as runner-up in 1991 with Jaguar) and Wurz, who, at 22 years old, became the youngest ever Le Mans overall winner.", 'Louis Meznarie | Louis Meznarie (January 14, 1930) is a former French engine preparation expert and a team owner entrant to 24 Hours of Le Mans.', 'Alexander Wurz | Alexander Wurz (born 15 February 1974) is an Austrian former professional racing driver, driver training expert and businessman. He competed in Formula One from until , and is also a two-time winner of the Le Mans 24 Hours.'], 'question': 'Which co-owner of Rainer-Wurz won Le Mans 24 Hours twice?', 'reasoning': 'The question asks about the co-owner of Rainer-Wurz who won Le Mans 24 Hours twice. The context provided mentions Alexander Wurz, who is the son of Rainer Wurz. According to the context, Alexander Wurz is a two-time winner of the Le Mans 24 Hours.', 'search_query': '"Alexander Wurz Le Mans wins"'}) (input_keys=None)]

